[[en:Kōreisai]]

{{unreferenced|date=December 2010}}
{{nihongo||皇霊祭|'''Kōreisai'''}}, or {{nihongo||春季|Shun-ki|Vernal}} and {{nihongo||秋季|Shū-ki|Autumnal}} Kōreisai, are days of worship in [[Japan]] that began in 1878 ({{Japanese year|1878}}) to pay respects to the [[List of Japanese monarchs|past emperors]] and [[Imperial House of Japan|imperial family members]]. It occurred on the spring and autumn [[equinox]]es of the anniversary of the person's death. After the 1948 passing of the Act on National Holidays, these days were marked in a non-religious manner as the [[Public holidays in Japan|national holiday]]s of [[Vernal Equinox Day]] and [[Autumnal Equinox Day]]. During the event, one prayed for good harvest in the spring and said [[Harvest festival|thankyou for the harvest]] in autumn.  The equinoxes were also the days of [[ancestor veneration in China]].

{{DEFAULTSORT:Koreisai}}
[[Category:March observances]]
[[Category:September observances]]
[[Category:Public holidays in Japan]]


{{Shinto-stub}}

