{{Japanese Imperial Rituals}}
{{nihongo||皇霊祭|'''Kōreisai'''}}, or {{nihongo||春季|Shun-ki|Vernal}} and {{nihongo||秋季|Shū-ki|Autumnal}} Kōreisai, are days of worship in [[Japan]] that began in 1878 to pay respects to the [[List of Japanese monarchs|past emperors]] and [[Imperial House of Japan|imperial family members]]. It occurred on the [[March equinox]] (spring equinox) and the [[September equinox]] (autumn equinox) of the anniversary of the person's death. After the 1948 passing of the Act on National Holidays, these days were marked in a non-religious manner as the [[Public holidays in Japan|national holidays]] of [[Vernal Equinox Day]] and [[Autumnal Equinox Day]]. During the event, one prayed for good harvest in the spring and said [[Harvest festival|thank you for the harvest]] in autumn.  The equinoxes were also the days of [[ancestor veneration in China]].<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20231209040242/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=9100</ref>

